c method gets generated in the companion class. There could be issues with Native Image, particularly regarding how it interacts with fully qualified class names and companion objects.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering companion objects**\\n\\nIf the process succeeds, it will return the companion object. However, this companion object isn't an ExtensionId, which poses a problem. If the library extensions throw a runtime error saying \\\"[...] is not ExtensionId,\\\" I need to ensure that it won't fall back to the Java singleton when that happens. This seems crucial for maintaining the expected behavior and avoiding unexpected outcomes in the application. I need to think about how to handle this scenario effectively.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying Scala and Java tests**\\n\\nI'm considering how ScalaCompile can compile both Scala and Java if the source includes Java, specifically in `src/test/java`. There's an ambiguity regarding the test source root for tests under `tests/src/.../2.6.21` versus `src/test/scala`. While Scala files should be in `src/test/scala`, it seems Java helpers can be included. I'm pondering if using a nested static class inside a JUnit test might work out since naming rules are key in avoiding the `$` character in test class names.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring test class structure**\\n\\nI'm wondering if using an inner class in a test is acceptable. It seems like a public static method might be generated, which could be problematic. Scala's nested objects or classes can be a bit odd, so I might consider keeping the Java nested static class separate. Instead, a top-level helper like `JavaSingletonTypedExtensionId.java` in the test package could work better. I should probably remove any Scala helper classes or objects to streamline things. The Java helper could have nested static extensions or be a package-private top-level class.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_g7G4b8ZJ